    "recap_headline": "Central Michigan University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "KENT, Ohio \u2013\nA heartbreaker for the Central Michigan baseball team in the opener of a three-game Mid-American Conference series.\nKent State scored six runs in the bottom of the ninth inning to overcame a 10-4 deficit, and then pushed across the winning run in the bottom of the 10\nth\nin handing the Chippewas an 11-10 loss on Friday at the Golden Flashes' Schoonover Stadium.\nThe teams play game 2 of the series on Saturday (3 p.m.) and then close the series on Sunday (1 p.m.).\nThe Chippewas, who are 7-8, 1-3 MAC, hit a season-high five home runs \u2013 two by\nZach Knowlton\n\u2013 in building their 10-4 lead.\nThe Golden Flashes (13-4, 3-1) scored six runs on five hits off two Chippewa pitchers in the bottom of the ninth.\nNolan Belcher doubled leading off the bottom of the 10\nth\nand then pinch runner Matt Thompson went third on a single. After a groundout and an intentional walk loaded the bases, Thompson scored when Kolton Schaller was hit by a pitch.\nBrady Krzciok\n,\nBryson Webb\nand\nSpencer Verburg\nalso homered for the Chippewas, who finished with 12 hits.\nIt was the second and third home runs of the season for Knowlton, the first for Verburg, the second for Webb, and the fifth for Krzciok, who shared the team lead with\nHarrison Bowman\n.\nKnowlton also tripled and finished with three RBI, while Verburg also had three hits. It was the second career three-hit day for both players, and the first time Knowlton has homered twice in a game as a Chippewa.\nThe Golden Flashes hit four home runs on a day with the wind blowing stiffly out to right field.\nThe loss spoiled another solid start by CMU freshman right-hander Logan Neiswonger, who allowed four runs on six hits and struck out a career-high 14 in seven innings. He left with the Chippewas leading, 8-4.\nNeiswonger's strikeout total tied for the most by a Chippewa pitcher since at least 2018. Keegan Batka also struck 14 in a 2-0 win over Northern Illinois on April 28, 2024.\nMax Hammond\n(0-2), who came on with one out in the ninth inning, took the loss. Gave Moczydlowski relieved Neiswonger. Moczydlowski and Hammond combined to surrender seven runs on seven hits."
  },
